




TY  - JOUR
T1  - What Did Smith Mean by the Invisible Hand?
AU  - Grampp, William D.
Y1  - 2000/06/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/262125
DO  - 10.1086/262125
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 441
EP  - 465
VL  - 108
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The invisible hand is not a power that makes the good of one the good of all, and it is not any of a number of other things it is said to be. It is simply the inducement a merchant has to keep his capital at home, thereby increasing the domestic capital stock and enhancing military power, both of which are in the public interest and neither of which he intended. Smith's exposition discloses how his rhetorical sallies could disfigure his economics, confuse his argument for free trade, and make him play fast and loose with facts and the ideas of others.
AB  - The invisible hand is not a power that makes the good of one the good of all, and it is not any of a number of other things it is said to be. It is simply the inducement a merchant has to keep his capital at home, thereby increasing the domestic capital stock and enhancing military power, both of which are in the public interest and neither of which he intended. Smith's exposition discloses how his rhetorical sallies could disfigure his economics, confuse his argument for free trade, and make him play fast and loose with facts and the ideas of others.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/262125
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/262125
Y2  - 2024/03/19
